      <h2>Calibration: Do You Need It?</h2>
      <p>Consumer and prosumer laser measures (under $200) are factory-calibrated and don't have user-serviceable calibration. They're sealed units. If you drop your laser measure from a significant height (6 ft+) onto concrete, the internal alignment can shift. Signs of calibration drift include:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Consistent bias in one direction (every measurement is 1/8" short)</li>
        <li>Inconsistent readings at the same distance</li>
        <li>Readings that don't match a known reference distance</li>
      </ul>
      <p>To check calibration: measure a known distance (a 50 ft tape measure pulled tight across a driveway or hallway). Compare the laser reading to the tape. If the difference exceeds the spec accuracy, the tool needs service. BOSCH offers calibration services through their service centers.</p>

      <h2>Summary: Accuracy Checklist</h2>
      <p>Before every critical measurement, run through this checklist:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Clean lens? ✓</li>
        <li>Battery >20%? ✓</li>
        <li>Reference point set correctly? ✓</li>
        <li>Target surface appropriate? ✓</li>
        <li>Beam perpendicular to target? ✓</li>
        <li>Tool stabilized (not handheld if possible)? ✓</li>
        <li>Take 3 readings and confirm consistency ✓</li>
      </ol>
      <p>Follow these steps and even a budget laser measure like the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0C76CPGC7?tag=sciencesolved-20">BOSCH GLM100-23</a> will deliver reliable, repeatable measurements. Skip the checklist — and a $200+ pro laser can still give you a bad number.</p>
